97
00:05:55,726 --> 00:06:01,827
So in the first few days of prototyping Soft Body, I got this beautiful gooey snake.

98
00:06:01,827 --> 00:06:06,108
And I don't know, I just immediately kind of liked it.

99
00:06:06,108 --> 00:06:09,229
It's very simple and it felt really good to move around.

100
00:06:09,229 --> 00:06:11,190
And actually, this is what it is.

101
00:06:11,190 --> 00:06:14,330
It's just a bunch of circles being spawned.

102
00:06:15,190 --> 00:06:18,792
And so you get a circle that like spawns every frame,

103
00:06:18,792 --> 00:06:19,512
and then that circle,

104
00:06:19,512 --> 00:06:22,353
the circle's radius will then grow for 10 frames,

105
00:06:22,353 --> 00:06:25,715
and then the circle's radius will start to shrink.

106
00:06:25,715 --> 00:06:26,395
And then every frame,

107
00:06:26,395 --> 00:06:29,436
there's about a 4% chance for the circle to start wobbling.

108
00:06:29,436 --> 00:06:31,577
And this is what gives the snake,

109
00:06:31,577 --> 00:06:35,499
it's kind of like gooey, organic feeling, the wobble.

110
00:06:36,505 --> 00:06:38,187
So I like this for two reasons.

111
00:06:38,187 --> 00:06:43,510
One, it's pretty, but also strange and lifelike and

112
00:06:43,510 --> 00:06:45,752
adorable, but not cute.

113
00:06:45,752 --> 00:06:48,414
So a visual thing.

114
00:06:48,414 --> 00:06:53,017
But the main thing was it just was a joy to control the body,

115
00:06:53,017 --> 00:06:55,358
especially with a controller.

116
00:06:55,358 --> 00:06:59,461
In fact, I would say that analog sticks really

117
00:06:59,461 --> 00:07:01,943
played a huge role in shaping soft bodies development.

118
00:07:01,943 --> 00:07:04,224
And I've always really, really loved analog sticks.

119
00:07:04,224 --> 00:07:05,525
They feel amazing.

120
00:07:06,284 --> 00:07:11,288
Especially on the PlayStation 4 and the Xbox One, these new ones, it has such a smooth

121
00:07:11,288 --> 00:07:11,608
action.

122
00:07:11,608 --> 00:07:14,911
I feel like you can do almost anything on an analog stick and it feels good.

123
00:07:14,911 --> 00:07:20,656
You can move it in a really fast circle or a slow circle around the barrier.

124
00:07:20,656 --> 00:07:25,400
I like the gentle resistance of the spring when you're pushing it in a direction.

125
00:07:25,400 --> 00:07:29,063
So I felt like I'd stumbled onto a great way of designing the core of the game.

126
00:07:29,063 --> 00:07:32,587
I could just design the game around what felt good to do with a controller.

127
00:07:34,597 --> 00:07:36,537
And so at first, development was centered

128
00:07:36,537 --> 00:07:37,457
around a single question.

129
00:07:37,457 --> 00:07:40,958
How can I make movement feel rewarding and great?

130
00:07:40,958 --> 00:07:44,219
So of course the controls were the central part of this,

131
00:07:44,219 --> 00:07:46,580
but I was trying to design obstacles and enemies

132
00:07:46,580 --> 00:07:49,841
that would encourage movement and sort of reinforce that,

133
00:07:49,841 --> 00:07:51,941
and also give some personality to the game.

134
00:07:51,941 --> 00:07:54,042
So from the shape of bullet patterns,

135
00:07:54,042 --> 00:07:56,502
like having them as circles or semi-circles

136
00:07:56,502 --> 00:07:58,723
so that people would move in a circle

137
00:07:58,723 --> 00:08:00,003
as opposed to in a straight line

138
00:08:00,003 --> 00:08:01,364
and they're just pushing themselves

139
00:08:01,364 --> 00:08:02,564
in some certain direction.

140
00:08:02,992 --> 00:08:07,654
to the sound when you paint walls, to the way that I designed like certain enemies.

141
00:08:07,654 --> 00:08:12,356
You know, from the beginning all these small refinements were meant to accentuate movement.

142
00:08:12,356 --> 00:08:17,518
And so here's a clip right now of like an enemy I designed in which, yeah, it's completely

143
00:08:17,518 --> 00:08:22,681
designed so that you're always circling it and that's like the fun thing that I found

144
00:08:22,681 --> 00:08:23,121
you could do.

145
00:08:23,121 --> 00:08:23,221
But

146
00:08:27,672 --> 00:08:30,934
what I actually define as rewarding and great.

147
00:08:30,934 --> 00:08:33,616
What does this actually mean to me?

148
00:08:33,616 --> 00:08:34,637
So of course it's like, you know,

149
00:08:34,637 --> 00:08:36,659
there's the games mechanics and there's rules.

150
00:08:36,659 --> 00:08:38,801
So like, there's stuff that's great when it's like,

151
00:08:38,801 --> 00:08:40,802
oh, it's not fussy when you paint a wall

152
00:08:40,802 --> 00:08:42,784
because the like painting radius is really big.

153
00:08:42,784 --> 00:08:45,266
Yeah, that's rewarding and great.

154
00:08:45,266 --> 00:08:46,867
And others, you know, small stuff

155
00:08:46,867 --> 00:08:48,789
that are about the aesthetics and whatnot.

156
00:08:48,789 --> 00:08:51,831
But really there was also this like emotional appeal

157
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:53,192
that I was trying to go for.

158
00:08:54,816 --> 00:08:58,918
So with games like Kerypt and Fez, I felt like there was something that was much more

159
00:08:58,918 --> 00:09:01,820
compelling than just like the mechanics in place.

160
00:09:01,820 --> 00:09:07,263
Like Fez, for instance, whenever I see a screenshot, I kind of have this feeling, you know, it

161
00:09:07,263 --> 00:09:12,887
kind of evokes this musical memory, like this time I spent with a game and I don't know,

162
00:09:12,887 --> 00:09:15,528
it's kind of like hearing an old song and remembering where you were at the time.

163
00:09:15,528 --> 00:09:19,010
And I think Fez does that really, really, really well.

164
00:09:19,010 --> 00:09:20,992
On the other hand, like something like Kerypt...

165
00:09:21,443 --> 00:09:25,146
is this really strange mood, and it's about puzzles,

166
00:09:25,146 --> 00:09:28,588
but even before you've solved a puzzle,

167
00:09:28,588 --> 00:09:32,411
even before you've gotten to the real gist of the game,

168
00:09:32,411 --> 00:09:35,513
it's still compelling, you still want to keep playing it,

169
00:09:35,513 --> 00:09:38,135
not just because it feels good to move around.

170
00:09:38,135 --> 00:09:40,297
So it was important to me that the game

171
00:09:40,297 --> 00:09:43,059
wasn't just some design fetishy achievement and elegance,

172
00:09:43,059 --> 00:09:45,760
but that it would have some sort of emotional energy as well,

173
00:09:45,760 --> 00:09:48,783
especially since I was really searching to find,

174
00:09:49,499 --> 00:09:52,782
energy to keep prototyping after this awful money money experience.

175
00:09:52,782 --> 00:09:57,648
So it is kind of strange to me though, I was thinking about this when I was putting the

176
00:09:57,648 --> 00:10:02,994
talk together, it's like I talk so much about like making the game feel great and like building

177
00:10:02,994 --> 00:10:07,539
it around these, this you know, controllers, really simple concept, it sounds so elegant,

178
00:10:07,539 --> 00:10:09,461
it sounds so like minimalist.

179
00:10:10,285 --> 00:10:16,012
You know, with all this energy spent on the controls and the tight movement and the fluid feelings and stuff,

180
00:10:16,012 --> 00:10:20,857
why would I choose to pursue this really intense challenge of controlling two things at the same time?

181
00:10:20,857 --> 00:10:26,803
It's something that seems to be completely in the opposite of a kind of a chilled out experience.

182
00:10:27,904 --> 00:10:32,126
I don't know if I have the greatest answer, but, you know, I was trying to make stuff,

183
00:10:32,126 --> 00:10:35,288
but I wasn't trying to, without overthinking it, you know.

184
00:10:35,288 --> 00:10:39,931
Part of staying in this great creative mind space was the possibility of having some kind

